Canter's con- jecture, ‘arvis,’ was warmly supported by Bentley. It has since been found in one MS. of no great antiquity. There is force in Bentley's argument, that Horace's indignation is moved not by Romans having borne arms against their country, ‘quod falsum et inauditum: but by their consenting to live and marry among their captors, ‘ obliti Romani nominis.⁷ The charge seemS, vv. 25, 30, 31, 36, to be rather that they are eowards than renegades. In the presence, however, of the MS. testimony he has not persuaded many of the editors.
